> - **Topic:** Access Modifiers (Public, Private, Protected)

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

**Access Modifiers** (also called *access specifiers*) in Java are reserved keywords that control the **visibility**, **accessibility**, and **scope** of classes, methods, constructors, and instance variables within a Java program. They are the primary mechanism by which Java enforces **Encapsulation** — one of the four foundational pillars of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP).

The four access levels supported by Java are:

- **`public`** — Most permissive access level
- **`protected`** — Intermediate access (inheritance-aware)
- **`default`** (package-private, no keyword) — Package-restricted
- **`private`** — Most restrictive access level

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** Module 2 explicitly emphasizes *Access Modifiers* as a prerequisite for understanding **Encapsulation**, **Data Hiding**, and **Inheritance visibility rules**. Questions typically appear in Part A (3 marks) and frequently combine with inheritance scenarios in Part B (14 marks).

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Building Security Pass"

Imagine a corporate office building with different security zones:

| Zone | Real-World Analogue | Java Equivalent |
|------|--------------------|-----------------|
| Public Lobby (anyone enters) | Reception open to all visitors | `public` |
| Employee Lounge (only staff) | Requires company ID | `default` (package) |
| Manager's Office (staff + their team) | Inheritance privilege | `protected` |
| CEO's Private Chamber (only the CEO) | Strict personal access | `private` |

> A `public` method is like the **building's main entrance** — anyone, anywhere, can use it. A `private` field is like the **CEO's personal vault** — only the CEO (the class itself) can touch it. A `protected` field is like a **department's shared folder** — accessible to the department and any branch office (subclass) that inherits from it.

### 1.3 Default Modifier (Implicit Package-Private)

> [!NOTE]
> When **no access modifier** is written before a class member, Java automatically assigns the **default** (also called *package-private*) access level. This is the most commonly overlooked modifier in KTU exams and frequently tested as a trick question.

---

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Four Modifiers — Operational Breakdown

#### **A. `public` Access Modifier**
- **Visibility:** Accessible from **any class**, in **any package**, anywhere in the application (and even outside the application via reflection, though that's beyond Module 2 scope).
- **Use Case:** Public API methods (e.g., `main()`, getter/setter methods exposed to external classes), constants intended for global use.
- **Restriction:** A `.java` source file can have **at most one `public` class**, and the file name **must match** that public class name.

#### **B. `private` Access Modifier**
- **Visibility:** Accessible **only within the same class** in which it is declared.
- **Use Case:** Data members (fields) meant to be hidden from external manipulation — the core of **encapsulation**.
- **Key Rule:** `private` members are **NOT** accessible by subclasses (a critical KTU exam pitfall!).

#### **C. `protected` Access Modifier**
- **Visibility:** Accessible within:
  1. The **same package**, AND
  2. **Subclasses** (even if the subclass is in a *different* package)
- **Use Case:** Template method patterns, methods meant to be overridden by subclasses, fields shared within a package and its descendants.

#### **D. `default` (Package-Private) Access Modifier**
- **Visibility:** Accessible **only within the same package**.
- **Use Case:** Helper classes, package-internal utility methods, default constructors.
- **Key Distinction:** Subclasses in a *different* package **cannot** access default members — this is what differentiates `default` from `protected`.

### 2.2 KTU High-Yield Access Control Matrix

The following table is the **single most important table** for KTU exams on this topic. Memorize the `Yes/No` entries:

| Modifier | Same Class | Same Package (Non-Subclass) | Same Package (Subclass) | Different Package (Subclass) | Different Package (Non-Subclass) |
|----------|:----------:|:---------------------------:|:-----------------------:|:----------------------------:|:--------------------------------:|
| `public` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| `protected` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| `default` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| `private` | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ No | ❌ No | ❌ No |

> [!NOTE]
> In the matrix above, **"Yes"** means the member is accessible; **"No"** means a compilation error will occur. Note the critical contrast: in row 2, `protected` and `default` behave **identically inside the same package** (both yield "Yes"), but diverge across packages — `protected` allows subclass access, `default` does not.

### 2.3 Scope Compatibility with Class Elements

| Class Element | Allowed Modifiers |
|--------------|------------------|
| Top-level Class | `public` or `default` only |
| Inner Class | `public`, `protected`, `default`, or `private` |
| Member Variable | All four modifiers |
| Method | All four modifiers |
| Constructor | All four modifiers |
| Interface (by default) | All methods are implicitly `public` |

### 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

In professional software engineering (e.g., building banking systems, IoT firmware, or Android apps), access modifiers are used to:
- **Protect sensitive data** (e.g., a `private double accountBalance;` field).
- **Define stable public APIs** (a `public boolean login(String user, String pwd)` method).
- **Enable framework extension** (`protected void onCreate()` in Android lifecycle methods).
- **Prevent tight coupling** between modules in different packages.

---

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthroughs

### 3.1 Worked Example 1: Predicting Compilation Success/Failure

**Problem:** Given two classes in **different packages**, determine the compilation outcome.

```java
// File 1: package com.ktu.bank;
package com.ktu.bank;
public class Account {
    private   double balance       = 5000.00;
    protected String accountType   = "Savings";
    public    String bankName      = "KTU Federal Bank";

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}
```

```java
// File 2: package com.ktu.atm;
package com.ktu.atm;
import com.ktu.bank.Account;

public class ATM extends Account {
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Bank: " + bankName);        // Line A
        System.out.println("Type: " + accountType);     // Line B
        System.out.println("Bal: " + getBalance());     // Line C
        System.out.println("Bal: " + balance);          // Line D
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Analysis:**

- **Line A (`bankName`):** `bankName` is declared `public`. Rule: accessible from any class, any package. ✅ **Compiles successfully**.

- **Line B (`accountType`):** `accountType` is declared `protected`. The class `ATM` is a **subclass** of `Account` (note `extends Account`) but resides in a **different package** (`com.ktu.atm`). Rule: `protected` members are accessible to subclasses in different packages **only through inheritance** (i.e., on the subclass instance, not on a parent reference). Here, we are accessing it directly via the name `accountType` from within a subclass method. ✅ **Compiles successfully**.

- **Line C (`getBalance()`):** `getBalance()` is `public` (a method declared inside a `public` class without an explicit modifier other than `public`). ✅ **Compiles successfully**. Note: We are *not* accessing the `private` field `balance` directly — we go through its public accessor.

- **Line D (`balance`):** `balance` is declared `private`. Rule: `private` members are accessible **only within the same class** (`Account` class). The class `ATM` is *not* the same class. ❌ **Compilation Error**: `balance has private access in com.ktu.bank.Account`.

### 3.2 Worked Example 2: Encapsulation with Getters/Setters (The "POJO Pattern")

**The Standard KTU Pattern** — converting a non-encapsulated class into a fully encapsulated one:

```java
// BEFORE (Poor encapsulation)
class Student {
    String name;       // default access — risky
    int rollNo;        // default access — risky
}
```

**Step 1: Make fields `private`.**

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    private int rollNo;
}
```

**Step 2: Provide `public` getter and setter methods for controlled access.**

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    private int rollNo;

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public int getRollNo() {
        return rollNo;
    }

    public void setRollNo(int rollNo) {
        if (rollNo > 0) {            // Validation logic — the power of encapsulation
            this.rollNo = rollNo;
        }
    }
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- Data is **hidden** from direct external modification.
- Validation can be **enforced** before assignment (e.g., rejecting negative roll numbers).
- The internal representation can **change freely** without breaking external code that uses the public getters.

### 3.3 Worked Example 3: The `protected` Cross-Package Trap

**Scenario:** Subclass `PremiumAccount` in package `com.ktu.premium` inherits from `Account` in `com.ktu.bank`.

```java
package com.ktu.premium;
import com.ktu.bank.Account;

public class PremiumAccount extends Account {
    public void demo() {
        // Accessing inherited protected field — works ONLY if accessed
        // via subclass reference, NOT via a parent-class reference.
        System.out.println(this.accountType);     // ✅ Works
    }

    public void anotherDemo(Account acc) {
        System.out.println(acc.accountType);      // ❌ Fails to compile
    }
}
```

**Explanation:** Even though `PremiumAccount` is a subclass, you **cannot** access a `protected` member of another `Account` object (a sibling instance) from a different package. The `protected` privilege through inheritance is granted **only for the subclass's own type**, not for arbitrary instances of the parent.

