## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Method Overriding** is a fundamental feature of *Runtime Polymorphism* (Dynamic Polymorphism) in Java wherein a **subclass (child class)** provides a **specific implementation** for a method that is **already declared** in its **superclass (parent class)**. The overridden method in the subclass must have the **exact same signature** (name, number of parameters, and parameter types) and **return type** (or a covariant return type) as the method in the parent class. The JVM resolves which version of the method to invoke **at runtime** based on the actual object type, not the reference type.

**Key Lexicon Used by KTU Examiners:**
- **Superclass / Parent Class / Base Class** — The class that originally declares the method.
- **Subclass / Child Class / Derived Class** — The class that provides the new implementation.
- **Overridden Method** — The method in the parent class.
- **Overriding Method** — The method redefined in the child class.
- **Dynamic Method Dispatch** — The mechanism by which the JVM decides at runtime which overridden method to call.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Remote Control Inheritance"

Imagine a **generic TV Remote** (Parent Class) that has a button labelled *"Power"*. By default, this remote simply turns a TV on or off. Now, a manufacturer creates a **Smart Remote** (Child Class) that **inherits** every button from the generic remote (including the *Power* button), but **redefines what happens** when *Power* is pressed — instead of just toggling the TV, it asks *"Which device would you like to control?"* and offers TV, Soundbar, or Streaming Box.

- The **button label** (method signature) is **identical** — you still press "Power".
- The **internal action** (method body) is **completely different** — it is *overridden*.
- The **user doesn't need to know** which remote they are holding; pressing the button works seamlessly.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why does this matter?** Method Overriding allows Java programs to achieve **"one interface, many implementations"** — the hallmark of polymorphism. A single method call behaves differently based on the actual object at runtime.

### 1.3 Runtime vs Compile-Time Decision

| Aspect | Method Overloading (Module 2) | Method Overriding (Module 3) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Binding Time** | Compile Time (Static Binding) | **Runtime (Dynamic Binding)** |
| **Signature** | Must differ (params) | **Must be identical** |
| **Class Relationship** | Same class | **Parent-Child (Inheritance)** |
| **KTU Term** | Compile-Time Polymorphism | **Runtime Polymorphism** |
| **Also called** | Static Polymorphism | **Dynamic Polymorphism** |

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

