## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Rule Sheet

### 2.1 The 10 Golden Rules of Method Overriding (Highest KTU Yield)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Examiners frequently frame 3-mark and 7-mark questions as *"List the rules of method overriding"* or *"Explain the rules with an example"*. Memorising these is non-negotiable.

1. **Same Method Signature** — The overriding method must have the **identical name** and **identical parameter list** (including order and types) as the overridden method.
2. **Inheritance is Mandatory** — There must be an **IS-A relationship** (extends keyword) between the classes. Method overriding cannot occur within a single class.
3. **Return Type Rule** — The return type must be **the same** as the parent method, or a **covariant return type** (a subclass of the parent's return type, introduced in Java 5).
4. **Access Modifier Cannot Be More Restrictive** — If the parent method is `public`, the child method cannot be `private`, `protected`, or package-private. The child method can only be `public` or **less restrictive** (e.g., parent `protected` → child `public`).
5. **Cannot Override `final` Methods** — A method declared `final` in the parent class is a *constant* and cannot be overridden.
6. **Cannot Override `static` Methods** — Static methods belong to the class, not the object. They can be **hidden**, not overridden. Attempting to override a static method results in *method hiding*, which is resolved at compile time.
7. **Cannot Override `private` Methods** — Private methods are not visible to the subclass, so they are essentially invisible and cannot participate in overriding.
8. **Exception Rule** — The overriding method can throw **the same**, **fewer**, or **narrower (subclass) checked exceptions** — but it **cannot throw new or broader checked exceptions** than the parent method.
9. **`abstract` Methods Must Be Overridden** — Any abstract method declared in an abstract class **must** be implemented (overridden) in the first concrete (non-abstract) subclass.
10. **Invoking Parent Version** — The `super.methodName()` call allows the child class to invoke the **exact parent version** of the overridden method, useful for extending behaviour rather than replacing it.

### 2.2 KTU Rule Cheat Sheet (Markdown Table)

| # | Rule | Allowed | Not Allowed |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Access Modifier | Same or **less restrictive** (parent `protected` → child `public`) | **More restrictive** (parent `public` → child `private`) |
| 2 | Return Type | Same type or **covariant** (subclass of return type) | **Unrelated** or **superclass** type |
| 3 | Exception | Same, **fewer**, or **subclass** checked exceptions | **New** or **broader (superclass)** checked exceptions |
| 4 | Method Signature | **Identical** name + parameter list | Different name, different params, swapped types |
| 5 | Final Method | Cannot override | `final` parent method **cannot** be redefined |
| 6 | Static Method | Can **hide** (not override) | Calling it via reference uses **reference type** (compile-time) |
| 7 | Private Method | Cannot be overridden (invisible to child) | Subclass can declare same method as **new method** |
| 8 | Abstract Method | **Must** be implemented in concrete subclass | Leaving it abstract propagates the abstractness |

### 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

> [!NOTE]
> Method overriding is the backbone of the **Strategy Pattern**, **Template Method Pattern**, and most **Dependency Injection** frameworks (Spring, Jakarta EE). The Java Collections Framework itself relies on overriding — when you call `hashCode()` or `equals()` on a `HashMap` key, you are benefiting from overridden implementations in classes like `String` and `Integer`. Without overriding, frameworks like JUnit (which uses dynamic proxies) could not function.

### 2.4 Dynamic Method Dispatch — The "Why It Works" Engine

Dynamic Method Dispatch is the **mechanism** by which overriding achieves runtime polymorphism. The reference variable type is checked at **compile time**, but the actual method invoked is determined at **runtime** based on the **object's real type**.

$$ \text{Reference Type (Compile-time check)} \rightarrow \text{Object Type (Runtime invocation)} $$

This is achieved internally by the JVM using a **vtable (virtual method table)**. Each class loaded into the JVM has a vtable that maps method signatures to actual method implementations. When an overridden method is called via a parent reference, the JVM uses the vtable to locate the correct method in the actual object's class.

