## 3. Step-by-Step Code Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Foundational Example — Shape, Circle, Rectangle

This is the **canonical KTU example**. Expect at least one exam variant of this in every cycle.

**Step 1:** Define the parent class with a method to be overridden.

```java
// Parent Class
class Shape {
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a generic Shape");
    }

    public double area() {
        return 0.0;
    }
}
```

**Step 2:** Create concrete subclasses that override the parent's methods.

```java
// Child Class 1
class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override  // Compiler-time safety annotation
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a Circle with radius " + radius);
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}

// Child Class 2
class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double length, width;

    public Rectangle(double length, double width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a Rectangle " + length + " x " + width);
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return length * width;
    }
}
```

**Step 3:** The polymorphic driver class demonstrates dynamic dispatch.

```java
public class PolymorphismDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Parent references, child objects — THE Classic KTU Setup
        Shape s1 = new Circle(5.0);
        Shape s2 = new Rectangle(4.0, 6.0);
        Shape s3 = new Shape();

        s1.draw();  // Output: Drawing a Circle with radius 5.0
        s2.draw();  // Output: Drawing a Rectangle 4.0 x 6.0
        s3.draw();  // Output: Drawing a generic Shape

        System.out.println("Circle area   : " + s1.area());
        System.out.println("Rectangle area: " + s2.area());
    }
}
```

**Step-by-step Trace (Mental Execution Table for Exams):**

| Line | Reference Variable | Compile-Time Type | Object Type (Runtime) | Method Invoked |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `s1.draw()` | `s1` | `Shape` | `Circle` | `Circle.draw()` |
| `s2.draw()` | `s2` | `Shape` | `Rectangle` | `Rectangle.draw()` |
| `s3.draw()` | `s3` | `Shape` | `Shape` | `Shape.draw()` |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Trick Question:** *"Which `draw()` is called for `s1`?"* — Many students answer `Shape.draw()`. The correct answer is `Circle.draw()` because the JVM uses **dynamic method dispatch** based on the actual object type, not the reference type.

### 3.2 The `super` Keyword — Partial Overriding

A common KTU Part B sub-question asks how to **extend** (not replace) parent behaviour.

```java
class Animal {
    public void speak() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes a sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void speak() {
        super.speak();  // Calls parent version FIRST
        System.out.println("Dog barks: Woof!");
    }
}

class Puppy extends Dog {
    @Override
    public void speak() {
        super.speak();  // Calls Dog's speak() (which itself calls Animal's)
        System.out.println("Puppy yelps: Yip yip!");
    }
}
```

**Execution Trace for `new Puppy().speak();`:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Output Sequence:} \quad & \text{Animal makes a sound} \\
& \text{Dog barks: Woof!} \\
& \text{Puppy yelps: Yip yip!}
\end{aligned}
$$

This is the **multi-level method chaining** technique. The keyword `super.speak()` is resolved at **compile time** (it always refers to the direct parent's version), while the call made through a reference variable exhibits **dynamic dispatch**.

### 3.3 Covariant Return Type — A Subtle Java 5+ Feature

```java
class Building {
    public Building getInstance() {
        return new Building();
    }
}

class House extends Building {
    @Override
    public House getInstance() {  // Covariant: House is-a Building
        return new House();
    }
}
```

The return type changed from `Building` to `House`. This is **legal** because `House` is a subclass of `Building`. The Java compiler accepts this under the **covariant return type** rule (introduced in J2SE 5.0).

### 3.4 Access Modifier Restriction Demonstration

```java
class Parent {
    protected void display() {  // protected
        System.out.println("Parent display");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    // @Override
    // private void display() { }  // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: more restrictive
    public void display() {       // ✅ ALLOWED: less restrictive
        System.out.println("Child display");
    }
}
```

The compiler produces: *"attempting to assign weaker access privileges; was protected"*. KTU questions often ask the student to **identify the error** in such code snippets.

### 3.5 Final, Static, and Private — "The Holy Trinity of Non-Overridable"

```java
class Vehicle {
    public final void start() {        // Cannot override
        System.out.println("Vehicle starts");
    }
    public static void service() {     // Can hide, not override
        System.out.println("Servicing Vehicle");
    }
    private void secretCode() {        // Not visible to child
        System.out.println("Secret code");
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    // public void start() { }        // ❌ Cannot override final method
    public static void service() {     // Hides parent's static method
        System.out.println("Servicing Car");
    }
    public void secretCode() {         // This is a NEW method, NOT override
        System.out.println("Car's secret");
    }
}
```

**Driver code that illustrates the difference:**

```java
Vehicle v = new Car();
v.service();  // Calls Vehicle.service() — STATIC uses REFERENCE type
v.start();    // Calls Vehicle.start() — final, cannot be overridden
```

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistake:** Students often write `v.service();` and expect it to call `Car.service()`. **No.** Static methods are resolved at **compile time** based on the reference type (`Vehicle`). The JVM does not perform dynamic dispatch for static methods. This is a frequent 3-mark question.

### 3.6 Analytical Matrix — Overriding vs Other OOP Features

| Feature | Overriding | Overloading | Hiding (Static) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Binding** | Runtime | Compile-time | Compile-time |
| **Signature** | Identical | Different | Identical (with `static`) |
| **Polymorphism Type** | Runtime (Dynamic) | Compile-time (Static) | None — just hiding |
| **Inheritance Needed** | Yes | No | Yes |
| **Resolution By** | Object type (JVM) | Argument type (Compiler) | Reference type (Compiler) |

