### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

> **Internal Choice Convention:** KTU ESE (End Semester Exam) typically presents TWO Part B questions per module, and the student answers **one** of them. Below are two fully-solved independent alternatives.

---

#### **Question A (14 Marks)** — [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]

**(a)** Explain the concept of method overriding in Java with suitable example. Discuss the rules to be followed while overriding a method. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

Method overriding allows a subclass to provide a **specific implementation** of a method declared in its parent class. The method in the subclass is said to **override** the method in the parent class. This is the foundation of **runtime polymorphism** in Java.

**Illustrative Example:**

```java
class Bank {
    double getRateOfInterest() {
        return 0.0;
    }
}

class SBI extends Bank {
    @Override
    double getRateOfInterest() {
        return 6.5;
    }
}

class HDFC extends Bank {
    @Override
    double getRateOfInterest() {
        return 7.0;
    }
}

public class BankTest {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Bank b;
        b = new SBI();
        System.out.println("SBI Rate: " + b.getRateOfInterest() + "%");
        b = new HDFC();
        System.out.println("HDFC Rate: " + b.getRateOfInterest() + "%");
    }
}
```

**Output:**
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{SBI Rate: } & 6.5\% \\
\text{HDFC Rate: } & 7.0\%
\end{aligned}
$$

**Rules for Method Overriding:**

1. The method must have the **same name and same parameter list** as the parent method.
2. The **return type** must be the same or a **covariant subtype**.
3. The **access level cannot be more restrictive** than the parent's method.
4. **Final, static, and private** methods cannot be overridden.
5. The overriding method must **not throw new or broader checked exceptions**.
6. **Abstract methods** must be overridden in the first concrete subclass.

**(b)** What is the role of the `super` keyword in method overriding? Write a Java program to demonstrate the use of `super` to call the overridden method from the subclass. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

The `super` keyword in Java is used to refer to the **immediate parent class** members. In the context of method overriding, `super.methodName()` is used to invoke the **parent class's version** of an overridden method. This is useful when the subclass wants to **extend** the parent's behaviour rather than completely replace it.

**Java Program:**

```java
class Employee {
    double salary = 30000;

    void work() {
        System.out.println("Employee works 8 hours a day");
    }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    double salary = 60000;  // Hides parent's salary

    @Override
    void work() {
        super.work();  // Calls Employee.work()
        System.out.println("Manager also conducts meetings");
    }

    void displaySalary() {
        System.out.println("Manager Salary: " + salary);
        System.out.println("Employee Salary (super): " + super.salary);
    }
}

public class SuperDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Manager m = new Manager();
        m.work();
        m.displaySalary();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text{Employee works 8 hours a day} \\
& \text{Manager also conducts meetings} \\
& \text{Manager Salary: 60000.0} \\
& \text{Employee Salary (super): 30000.0}
\end{aligned}
$$

The keyword `super.work()` explicitly invokes the parent's `work()` method, preserving the original behaviour, while the subclass adds its own functionality.

---

#### **Question B (14 Marks)** — [KTU University Exam - May 2024]

**(a)** What is Dynamic Method Dispatch? Explain with a real-world example and a Java program demonstrating runtime polymorphism. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

**Dynamic Method Dispatch** is the process by which the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) decides at **runtime** which overridden method to invoke. The compiler checks that the method exists in the **reference type**, but the actual method executed corresponds to the **object type** to which the reference points.

**Real-World Example:**
Consider a **payment gateway** system. A parent class `Payment` defines a method `processPayment()`. Different subclasses — `CreditCardPayment`, `UPIPayment`, `NetBankingPayment` — override this method with their specific logic. At runtime, the gateway invokes the correct method based on the user's chosen payment method.

**Java Program:**

```java
class Payment {
    void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing generic payment of " + amount);
    }
}

class CreditCardPayment extends Payment {
    @Override
    void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Credit Card payment processed: " + amount);
        System.out.println("Charging 2% processing fee.");
    }
}

class UPIPayment extends Payment {
    @Override
    void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("UPI payment processed: " + amount);
        System.out.println("No processing fee for UPI.");
    }
}

public class PaymentGateway {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Payment p;  // Single reference, multiple behaviours

        p = new CreditCardPayment();
        p.processPayment(2500.00);  // Calls CreditCardPayment version

        p = new UPIPayment();
        p.processPayment(1500.00);  // Calls UPIPayment version
    }
}
```

**Output:**
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text{Credit Card payment processed: 2500.0} \\
& \text{Charging 2\% processing fee.} \\
& \text{UPI payment processed: 1500.0} \\
& \text{No processing fee for UPI.}
\end{aligned}
$$

**(b)** Explain why `static`, `final`, and `private` methods cannot be overridden in Java. Provide a code example for each case. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

**1. `final` Methods:**
A method declared `final` in a class **cannot be overridden** by subclasses. The `final` keyword indicates the method's implementation is **complete and final**, preventing any modification. This is a design choice that allows the original developer to **lock down** critical behaviour.

```java
class MathConstants {
    public final double getPI() {
        return 3.14159;
    }
}

class AdvancedMath extends MathConstants {
    // @Override
    // public double getPI() { return 3.14; }  // ❌ Compile error
}
```

**2. `static` Methods:**
Static methods belong to the **class**, not to instances. They are resolved at **compile time** based on the reference type, not the object. A subclass can declare a static method with the same signature, but this is called **method hiding**, not overriding. The JVM does **not** perform dynamic dispatch for static methods.

```java
class Utility {
    public static void print() {
        System.out.println("Utility.print()");
    }
}

class SubUtility extends Utility {
    public static void print() {  // Hides, not overrides
        System.out.println("SubUtility.print()");
    }
}

public class StaticTest {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Utility u = new SubUtility();
        u.print();  // Calls Utility.print() — compile-time binding
    }
}
```

**3. `private` Methods:**
Private methods are **not visible** to subclasses. Because the subclass cannot even see the method, it cannot override it. If the subclass declares a method with the same signature, it is treated as an **entirely new method** in the subclass, not an override.

```java
class Secure {
    private void secret() {
        System.out.println("Secure.secret()");
    }
}

class Insecure extends Secure {
    public void secret() {  // NEW method, not an override
        System.out.println("Insecure.secret()");
    }
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Confusing `static` overriding with hiding** — Writing *"static methods can be overridden"* costs full marks on the question. Use the precise term: *method hiding*.
> 2. **Forgetting the `@Override` annotation** — While not a compilation error to omit it, KTU examiners look for it as evidence of intent. Always include it in your code listings.
> 3. **Stating "return type must be the same"** — This is incomplete. Mention **covariant return types** for full marks.
> 4. **Missing the exception rule** — Many students list access modifier and return type rules but forget to mention the **checked exception rule**, which is worth 1–2 marks.
> 5. **Confusing reference type with object type in output tracing** — The output is determined by the **object type**, not the reference type, in the case of instance method calls.

---

### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Must Memorise Before Exam:**

- **Definition:** Method overriding = subclass redefines a parent method with the **same signature** to achieve **runtime polymorphism**.
- **Core Mechanism:** Achieved via **Dynamic Method Dispatch**; resolved at **runtime** by the JVM using the **object's actual type**.
- **Annotation:** Always use `@Override` to inform the compiler of your intent and catch signature mismatches early.
- **Signature Rule:** Identical name + identical parameter list (types and order).
- **Return Type:** Identical **OR** covariant (subclass of original return type).
- **Access Modifier:** Cannot be **more restrictive** in the child (parent `public` → child `public` or N/A; parent `protected` → child `protected` or `public`).
- **Cannot Override:** `final` methods, `static` methods (only hidden), `private` methods (treated as new).
- **Exception Rule:** Can throw the same, fewer, or **narrower (subclass) checked exceptions** — never new or broader ones.
- **`super` keyword:** Used as `super.methodName()` to invoke the **parent's exact version** of an overridden method (compile-time binding).
- **Abstract Methods:** If parent has abstract methods, the **first concrete subclass must override** all of them; otherwise, the subclass must also be declared `abstract`.
- **Polymorphic Declaration:** `Parent ref = new Child();` — Reference type is checked at compile time; the method invoked is based on object type at runtime.
- **Static Binding for Static Methods:** Even with `Parent ref = new Child();`, calling a static method via `ref` invokes the **parent's static method**, not the child's.
- **Multi-level Chaining:** `super` always refers to the **immediate parent**, allowing chaining like `Puppy → Dog → Animal` for layered behaviour extension.
- **Common Real-World Use Cases:** Frameworks (Spring, JUnit), Collections (`equals`, `hashCode`, `toString`), Strategy Pattern, Template Method Pattern.
- **KTU 2024 Favourite Question Pattern:** *"Differentiate between method overloading and method overriding"* — always appears as a 3-marker in Part A.

