# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 🧩 The Two Categories of Custom Exceptions

### Category A: Checked Custom Exception (extends `Exception`)

Extending `java.lang.Exception` makes your custom exception a **checked** exception. The Java compiler will enforce that any method which throws it must either:

- Handle it with a `try-catch` block, **OR**
- Declare it in the method signature using the `throws` keyword.

**Use Case:** When the caller **should be able to recover** from the condition (e.g., `InvalidLoginException`, `FileSizeLimitExceededException`).

### Category B: Unchecked Custom Exception (extends `RuntimeException`)

Extending `java.lang.RuntimeException` makes your custom exception an **unchecked** exception. The compiler does **not** enforce handling or declaration.

**Use Case:** When the error indicates a **programming bug** or unrecoverable logic flaw (e.g., `InvalidConfigurationException`, `NullConfigurationException`).

## 📐 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| **#** | **Component** | **Syntax / Formula** | **Purpose / When to Use** |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Custom Checked Exception | `class MyEx extends Exception { }` | Compile-time enforced handling |
| 2 | Custom Unchecked Exception | `class MyEx extends RuntimeException { }` | Runtime, no compiler enforcement |
| 3 | Throw an Exception | `throw new MyException("msg");` | Explicitly trigger the exception |
| 4 | Declare in Method | `void m() throws MyException { }` | Inform caller of possible exception |
| 5 | Constructor Pattern (Message) | `MyEx(String s) { super(s); }` | Pass error message to parent |
| 6 | Constructor Pattern (Cause) | `MyEx(String s, Throwable c) { super(s, c); }` | Enable exception chaining |
| 7 | Multi-Catch | `catch (E1 \vert E2 e) { }` | Handle multiple exceptions uniformly |
| 8 | Rethrow | `throw e;` inside `catch` | Pass exception to higher handler |
| 9 | Custom Field in Exception | `private int errorCode;` | Carry application-specific data |
| 10 | Try-with-Resources | `try (Resource r = new Resource()) { }` | Auto-close resources (since Java 7) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Tip:** When asked "How to create a custom exception?", the **expected answer must always include the `super(message)` call** in the constructor. Omitting it is the #1 reason students lose marks.

## 🏗️ Why & How — Step-by-Step Reasoning

### Why `super(message)`?

The `Throwable` superclass stores the detail message in a private field. By calling `super(message)`, you delegate the message-storing responsibility to the parent, ensuring it is available via `getMessage()`.

### Why Use `serialVersionUID`?

> [!NOTE]
> Custom exceptions are **Serializable** by inheritance from `Throwable`. If you do not declare `private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;`, the compiler will warn (`The serializable class MyException does not declare a static final serialVersionUID field`). For KTU exams, it is **best practice** to include it.

### Why Distinguish Checked vs Unchecked?

The distinction maps to a real engineering trade-off: **Checked** exceptions force API users to think about error recovery (good for recoverable conditions). **Unchecked** exceptions keep code clean (good for programming errors). KTU exam questions often test this judgment.

### Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Banking Systems:** `InsufficientFundsException`, `InvalidAccountNumberException`
- **E-Commerce:** `OutOfStockException`, `InvalidCouponException`
- **Network Programming:** `ConnectionTimeoutException`, `ProtocolViolationException`
- **Form Validation:** `InvalidEmailException`, `WeakPasswordException`
- **Database Apps:** `DuplicateKeyException`, `RecordNotFoundException`

