> [!WARNING]
> **🚨 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout**
> 
> Students **commonly lose marks** in Custom Exception questions due to these mistakes:
> 
> 1. **Forgetting `super(message)` in the constructor** — Without this, `getMessage()` returns `null` and the exception is functionally useless. (Loss: 1–2 marks)
> 2. **Declaring `throws` for an unchecked exception** — This is syntactically allowed but logically wrong. Unchecked exceptions should NOT be declared. (Loss: 1 mark)
> 3. **Confusing `throw` and `throws`** — `throw` is followed by an **object**; `throws` is followed by a **class name**. Writing `throw MyException` is a compile error. (Loss: 1–2 marks)
> 4. **Forgetting `serialVersionUID`** — Causes a compiler warning; while not an error, examiners deduct for not following best practice. (Loss: 0.5–1 mark)
> 5. **Not handling exception chaining properly** — When asked about wrapping, students often forget to pass the cause to `super(message, cause)`, breaking the chain. (Loss: 2 marks)
> 6. **Choosing wrong parent class** — Extending `Exception` when `RuntimeException` is needed (or vice versa) changes compile-time behavior. (Loss: 1–2 marks)
> 7. **Missing try-catch in `main`** — When testing the exception in `main`, students forget to wrap the call in try-catch, leading to compile errors for checked exceptions. (Loss: 1 mark)

