## 🎯 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Custom Exceptions**

### ✅ Definition & Purpose
- Custom Exception = User-defined class extending `Exception` or `RuntimeException`.
- Used for **domain-specific** error modeling that built-in exceptions cannot express.

### ✅ The Two Flavors
- **Checked** → `extends Exception` → Compiler enforces handling → `throws` keyword needed.
- **Unchecked** → `extends RuntimeException` → No compiler enforcement → Cleaner code.

### ✅ Mandatory Constructor Pattern
- Always call **`super(message)`** to store the error message.
- Best practice: include **`serialVersionUID`**.
- Recommended 4 constructors: no-arg, message-only, message+cause, custom-fields.

### ✅ Critical Keywords
- **`throw`** — followed by `new ExceptionObject` — used **inside** method body.
- **`throws`** — followed by class names — used **in** method signature.

### ✅ Exception Chaining
- Wrap low-level exceptions in high-level custom ones using `super(message, cause)`.
- Retrieve original via `e.getCause()`.

### ✅ Custom Fields
- Add private fields like `errorCode`, `invalidValue`, `timestamp` for richer diagnostics.
- Always provide public getters.

### ✅ Best Practices
- Name exceptions descriptively ending in `Exception` (e.g., `InvalidEmailException`).
- Never swallow exceptions silently (always log or rethrow).
- Document custom exceptions in Javadoc.

### ✅ Common KTU Exam Traps
- Forgetting `super(message)` → null message.
- Throwing a class instead of an object → compile error.
- Declaring `throws` for `RuntimeException` subclasses → unnecessary code.
- Missing `try-catch` in `main` for checked custom exceptions → compile error.

### ✅ Must-Remember Formulas
- `throw new XException("msg");` — triggers.
- `void m() throws XException { }` — declares.
- `super(message);` — must be first line in custom exception constructor.
- `e.getCause()` — retrieves chained cause.
- `e.getMessage()` — retrieves stored message.

