## SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The `List` Interface – Ordered, Indexed, Duplicates Allowed

The `List` interface extends `Collection` and adds **positional** and **list-iterator** operations. Implementations in KTU syllabus:

| Implementation | Internal Structure | Key Strength | Key Weakness |
|---|---|---|---|
| `ArrayList` | Resizable array | **O(1) random access** via index | Slow insertions/deletions in the middle |
| `LinkedList` | Doubly-linked list | **O(1) insertion/deletion** at ends | Slow random access (O(n)) |
| `Vector` | Synchronized resizable array | Thread-safe | Legacy class, slow due to synchronization |
| `Stack` | Extends `Vector` (LIFO) | Models a stack | Legacy; prefer `Deque` |

**Core List Methods (must memorize):**
- `add(int index, E element)` – inserts at position
- `get(int index)` – retrieves element
- `set(int index, E element)` – replaces element
- `remove(int index)` – removes by position
- `indexOf(Object o)` – returns first occurrence index
- `subList(int from, int to)` – returns a view (not a copy)

### 2.2 The `Set` Interface – No Duplicates, Mathematical Abstraction

A `Set` models the mathematical concept of a set $\{x \mid P(x)\}$. The critical contract is that **no two elements can be equal** (equality tested via `equals()` AND `hashCode()` for hashed sets).

| Implementation | Internal Structure | Ordering | Null Allowed? |
|---|---|---|---|
| `HashSet` | Hash table (backed by `HashMap`) | **No order** guaranteed | Yes (one only) |
| `LinkedHashSet` | Hash table + linked list | **Insertion order** preserved | Yes (one only) |
| `TreeSet` | Red-Black tree | **Sorted** (natural or custom) | No (throws `NullPointerException`) |

> [!NOTE]
> **How `HashSet` achieves uniqueness:** When you call `set.add(obj)`, Java calls `obj.hashCode()` to find the bucket, then `obj.equals()` to check for collision duplicates. This is a favorite KTU 2-mark question.

### 2.3 The `Map` Interface – Key-to-Value Mappings

`Map<K, V>` stores pairs $(k, v)$ where $k \in K$ and $v \in V$, and $K$ contains no duplicates.

| Implementation | Internal Structure | Ordering | Thread-Safe? | Allows Null? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `HashMap` | Hash table | No order | No | Key: one null; Value: many nulls |
| `LinkedHashMap` | Hash table + linked list | Insertion / access order | No | Yes |
| `TreeMap` | Red-Black tree | Sorted by keys | No | No (keys) |
| `Hashtable` | Synchronized hash table | No order | Yes (legacy) | **No nulls at all** |

**Core Map Methods (must memorize):**
- `put(K key, V value)` – inserts or updates
- `get(Object key)` – returns value or `null`
- `containsKey(Object key)` – existence check on keys
- `containsValue(Object value)` – existence check on values
- `keySet()` – returns `Set<K>` view of all keys
- `values()` – returns `Collection<V>` view of all values
- `entrySet()` – returns `Set<Map.Entry<K, V>>` view of pairs

### 2.4 The KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet (Time Complexity)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This table is the **single most expected** question on this topic in KTU ESE. Memorize it cold.

| Operation | `ArrayList` | `LinkedList` | `HashSet` | `TreeSet` | `HashMap` | `TreeMap` |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Add | O(1) amortized | O(1) | O(1) avg | O(log n) | O(1) avg | O(log n) |
| Remove by value | O(n) | O(n) | O(1) avg | O(log n) | O(1) avg | O(log n) |
| Remove by index | O(n) | O(n) | — | — | — | — |
| Get / Search | O(1) | O(n) | O(1) avg | O(log n) | O(1) avg | O(log n) |
| Contains | O(n) | O(n) | O(1) avg | O(log n) | O(1) avg | O(log n) |
| Iteration | O(n) | O(n) | O(n) | O(n) | O(n) | O(n) |

**Notation legend:**  
- $O(1)$ → constant time (does not depend on size)  
- $O(\log n)$ → logarithmic time (very fast, tree-based)  
- $O(n)$ → linear time (grows with size)

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **List (`ArrayList`)** → Storing employee records in an HR system where you frequently jump to record #500.
- **Set (`HashSet`)** → Maintaining a list of unique IP addresses that have visited a web server (deduplication).
- **Map (`HashMap`)** → Implementing a cache (key = query string, value = response) in a web server.
- **Map (`TreeMap`)** → Building a phone directory sorted alphabetically by name.
- **`LinkedList`** → Implementing an *undo* stack in a text editor (frequent insertions/removals at the head).
