> This section is exhaustive. Every line of code is annotated with the **operational logic** — exactly how KTU board examiners expect answers to be written.

### 3.1 Detailed Analysis: `ArrayList` Operations

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Iterator;

public class ArrayListDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // STEP 1: Create a generic ArrayList of Strings
        // Logic: The <String> is a type parameter enforcing that
        // only String objects can be stored. The diamond operator <>
        // on the right side (Java 7+) infers the type.
        List<String> cities = new ArrayList<>();

        // STEP 2: Add elements (appends to the end)
        cities.add("Kochi");
        cities.add("Trivandrum");
        cities.add("Kozhikode");
        System.out.println("After adds: " + cities);

        // STEP 3: Insert at a specific index (shifts elements right)
        cities.add(1, "Thrissur");
        System.out.println("After insert at index 1: " + cities);

        // STEP 4: Access by index (O(1) operation)
        String firstCity = cities.get(0);
        System.out.println("First city: " + firstCity);

        // STEP 5: Replace an element
        cities.set(0, "Ernakulam");
        System.out.println("After replacement: " + cities);

        // STEP 6: Remove by index
        cities.remove(2);
        System.out.println("After remove index 2: " + cities);

        // STEP 7: Iterate using enhanced for-loop
        System.out.print("Iteration: ");
        for (String city : cities) {
            System.out.print(city + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();

        // STEP 8: Iterate using Iterator (safe during modification)
        Iterator<String> it = cities.iterator();
        System.out.print("Iterator: ");
        while (it.hasNext()) {
            System.out.print(it.next() + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
}
```

**Logical Trace of Execution:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Initial state} &: \text{ArrayList capacity=10, size=0} \\
\text{After 3 adds} &: \text{size=3, internal array = ["Kochi", "Trivandrum", "Kozhikode"]} \\
\text{After add(1, "Thrissur")} &: \text{size=4, ["Kochi", "Thrissur", "Trivandrum", "Kozhikode"]} \\
\text{After set(0, "Ernakulam")} &: \text{["Ernakulam", "Thrissur", "Trivandrum", "Kozhikode"]} \\
\text{After remove(2)} &: \text{size=3, ["Ernakulam", "Thrissur", "Kozhikode"]} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.2 Detailed Analysis: `LinkedList` as both List and Deque

```java
import java.util.LinkedList;
import java.util.Deque;

public class LinkedListDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        LinkedList<String> tasks = new LinkedList<>();

        // Treat as a stack (LIFO)
        tasks.push("Task A");    // pushes onto the head
        tasks.push("Task B");
        tasks.push("Task C");
        // Stack top -> bottom: Task C, Task B, Task A

        System.out.println("Top of stack: " + tasks.peek()); // Task C
        System.out.println("Popped: " + tasks.pop());        // Task C removed

        // Treat as a queue (FIFO)
        Deque<String> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        queue.offer("First");    // adds to tail
        queue.offer("Second");
        queue.offer("Third");
        System.out.println("Head of queue: " + queue.peek()); // First
        System.out.println("Polled: " + queue.poll());        // First removed
    }
}
```

**Why `LinkedList`?** Each node is a doubly-linked structure:

$$
\text{Node} = \{\texttt{data}, \texttt{prev} \rightarrow, \rightarrow \texttt{next}\}
$$

This makes insertion at the head or tail a pure $O(1)$ pointer-rewiring operation, regardless of the list size.

### 3.3 Detailed Analysis: `HashSet` – Uniqueness via Hashing

```java
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class HashSetDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Set<String> uniqueNames = new HashSet<>();

        // Logic: HashSet uses a HashMap internally.
        // When you add("Anu"), Java computes hashCode() of "Anu",
        // determines the bucket, and if !equals() any existing
        // element, the entry is stored.
        uniqueNames.add("Anu");
        uniqueNames.add("Binu");
        uniqueNames.add("Anu"); // Duplicate! Will NOT be added.

        System.out.println("Size: " + uniqueNames.size()); // 2
        System.out.println("Contains Anu? " + uniqueNames.contains("Anu")); // true

        // Remove an element
        uniqueNames.remove("Anu");
        System.out.println("After remove: " + uniqueNames);
    }
}
```

**Mathematical model of `hashCode()`:**  
For any object $o$ in a `HashSet`, the storage location is determined by:

$$
\text{bucket\_index} = (o.\text{hashCode}() \mod \text{capacity}) \ge 0
$$

If two distinct objects have the same bucket (collision), `equals()` is invoked as a tie-breaker.

### 3.4 Detailed Analysis: `TreeSet` – Sorted Set with Natural Ordering

```java
import java.util.TreeSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class TreeSetDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Set<Integer> sortedNumbers = new TreeSet<>();
        // TreeSet stores elements in sorted (ascending) order
        sortedNumbers.add(50);
        sortedNumbers.add(10);
        sortedNumbers.add(30);
        sortedNumbers.add(20);

        System.out.println(sortedNumbers); // [10, 20, 30, 50]
        // Note: duplicates would be ignored
    }
}
```

**Underlying data structure:** A self-balancing **Red-Black Tree**. For $n$ elements, the height of the tree is bounded by:

$$
h \le 2 \cdot \log_2(n+1)
$$

This guarantees that `add`, `remove`, and `contains` all run in $O(\log n)$ time.

### 3.5 Detailed Analysis: `HashMap` – The Most-Used Map

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class HashMapDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Map: Roll Number (Integer) -> Student Name (String)
        Map<Integer, String> studentDirectory = new HashMap<>();

        // STEP 1: Insert key-value pairs
        studentDirectory.put(101, "Anu");
        studentDirectory.put(102, "Binu");
        studentDirectory.put(103, "Chinu");

        // STEP 2: Updating an existing key (overwrites the value)
        studentDirectory.put(102, "Bindu");

        // STEP 3: Retrieve a value
        System.out.println("Roll 101: " + studentDirectory.get(101));

        // STEP 4: Check existence
        System.out.println("Has roll 104? " + studentDirectory.containsKey(104));

        // STEP 5: Iterate using entrySet() - most efficient
        System.out.println("Directory contents:");
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, String> entry : studentDirectory.entrySet()) {
            System.out.println("  " + entry.getKey() + " -> " + entry.getValue());
        }

        // STEP 6: Get all keys and values
        System.out.println("All rolls: " + studentDirectory.keySet());
        System.out.println("All names: " + studentDirectory.values());
    }
}
```

**Final state of the directory after execution:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
&\{101 \rightarrow \text{Anu},\ 102 \rightarrow \text{Bindu},\ 103 \rightarrow \text{Chinu}\} \\
&\text{keySet()} = \{101, 102, 103\} \\
&\text{values()} = \{\text{Anu}, \text{Bindu}, \text{Chinu}\} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.6 The `Comparable` vs `Comparator` Distinction (Sorting Custom Objects)

```java
import java.util.*;

class Student implements Comparable<Student> {
    int rollNo;
    String name;
    Student(int r, String n) { rollNo = r; name = n; }

    // Natural ordering: by roll number
    @Override
    public int compareTo(Student other) {
        return Integer.compare(this.rollNo, other.rollNo);
    }
    @Override
    public String toString() { return rollNo + ":" + name; }
}

public class SortingDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Student> list = new ArrayList<>();
        list.add(new Student(3, "Chinu"));
        list.add(new Student(1, "Anu"));
        list.add(new Student(2, "Binu"));

        // Natural order (uses compareTo)
        Collections.sort(list);
        System.out.println("Natural order: " + list);

        // Custom order: by name (uses Comparator)
        Collections.sort(list, new Comparator<Student>() {
            @Override
            public int compare(Student a, Student b) {
                return a.name.compareTo(b.name);
            }
        });
        System.out.println("By name: " + list);
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Comparable vs Comparator:**  
> - `Comparable` → defines the **natural/default** ordering inside the class itself (`compareTo`).  
> - `Comparator` → defines an **external/custom** ordering outside the class (`compare`). Used when you cannot modify the source class or need multiple sort orders.

### 3.7 Analytical Matrix: Choosing the Right Collection

| If you need... | Use this... | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Fast random access by index | `ArrayList` | Backed by array, $O(1)$ get |
| Frequent insertions at head/tail | `LinkedList` | $O(1)$ at ends, doubly-linked |
| Uniqueness, no order | `HashSet` | $O(1)$ add/contains via hashing |
| Uniqueness, insertion order | `LinkedHashSet` | Hash table + linked list |
| Uniqueness, sorted order | `TreeSet` | Red-Black tree, $O(\log n)$ |
| Key-value lookup, no order | `HashMap` | $O(1)$ get/put via hashing |
| Key-value, sorted by key | `TreeMap` | Red-Black tree, $O(\log n)$ |
| Thread-safe key-value | `Hashtable` or `ConcurrentHashMap` | Legacy vs modern |

### 3.8 Common Pitfall: `equals()` and `hashCode()` Contract

If you place custom objects into a `HashSet` or use them as keys in a `HashMap`, you **must** override **both**:

$$
\text{If } a.\text{equals}(b) \text{ is true} \Rightarrow a.\text{hashCode}() = b.\text{hashCode}()
$$

Violating this contract causes the set/map to behave incorrectly — duplicates may "leak" through because they end up in different buckets.
