> **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**

**Q2. What is the difference between `Comparable` and `Comparator` interfaces in Java? (3 Marks)**

**Model Answer:**

- **`Comparable<T>`** (in `java.lang`): Provides the **natural/default ordering** of objects. The class itself implements it and overrides the `compareTo(T o)` method. Only **one** sort sequence can be defined per class.
- **`Comparator<T>`** (in `java.util`): Provides a **custom/external** ordering. It is implemented as a separate object passed to `Collections.sort()` or `list.sort()`. **Multiple** sort sequences can be defined for the same class.
- **Key signature difference:** `compareTo` has **one parameter** (compares `this` with argument); `compare` has **two parameters**.

