### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each – Internal Choice)

> **[KTU University Exam – May 2024, Module 4 Comprehensive Question]**

#### **Question A (14 Marks)**

**(a)** Explain the Java Collections Framework hierarchy with a neat diagram. List the key interfaces and their main implementations. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

The Java Collections Framework (JCF) is a unified architecture in `java.util` for storing and manipulating groups of objects. The hierarchy is:

1. **`Iterable`** (root) → declares `iterator()` method.
2. **`Collection`** (extends `Iterable`) → parent of `List`, `Set`, `Queue`.
3. **`List`** → ordered, allows duplicates. Implementations: `ArrayList`, `LinkedList`, `Vector`, `Stack`.
4. **`Set`** → no duplicates. Implementations: `HashSet`, `LinkedHashSet`, `TreeSet`.
5. **`Queue`** → FIFO ordering. Implementations: `PriorityQueue`, `LinkedList` (also implements `Deque`).
6. **`Map`** → separate hierarchy (not a `Collection`). Key-value pairs. Implementations: `HashMap`, `TreeMap`, `Hashtable`, `LinkedHashMap`.

**Why `Map` is not a `Collection`:** Because `Map` works on key-value pairs, while `Collection` methods like `add(Object)` expect a single element.

**Algorithms** like `Collections.sort()`, `Collections.shuffle()`, `Collections.reverse()` work on these structures.

**(b)** Write a Java program to create an `ArrayList` of student objects (with `rollNo` and `name`), add 5 students, sort them by roll number using `Comparable`, and display them. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

```java
import java.util.*;

class Student implements Comparable<Student> {
    int rollNo;
    String name;
    Student(int r, String n) { rollNo = r; name = n; }

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Student other) {
        return Integer.compare(this.rollNo, other.rollNo);
    }
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return rollNo + " - " + name;
    }
}

public class StudentListDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<Student> list = new ArrayList<>();
        list.add(new Student(105, "Anu"));
        list.add(new Student(101, "Binu"));
        list.add(new Student(110, "Chinu"));
        list.add(new Student(103, "Dinu"));
        list.add(new Student(108, "Esha"));

        Collections.sort(list); // uses compareTo

        System.out.println("Sorted by roll number:");
        for (Student s : list) {
            System.out.println(s);
        }
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Sorted by roll number:
101 - Binu
103 - Dinu
105 - Anu
108 - Esha
110 - Chinu
```

